{"chunk_id": "416ca259-f424-4d33-83b0-830432749278", "source_database": "ICMR", "document_title": "ICMR_NIN_Dietary_Guidelines_Real.pdf", "publication_version": "Latest", "chunk_sequence_number": 101, "content_type": "Medical Guideline", "language": "English", "text": "breast-milk, providing sufficient nutrients are known as supplementary or complementary foods. These could be liquids like milk or semi-solids like 'kheer' in the case of infants or solid preparations like rice etc., in the case of children over the age of one year. At birth, mother's milk alone is adequate for the infant. Requirements of all the nutrients progressively increase with the infant's growth. Simultaneously, the breast- milk secretion in the mother comes down with time. Thus, infants are deprived of adequate nutrients due to the dual factors of increased nutrient requirements and decreased availability of breast-milk. Usually, these changes occur at about 6 months of age. Hence, promotion of optimal growth in infants, calls for introduction of adequate food supplements in", "embedding": [-0.00015330230235122144, -0.04694794863462448, -0.04606518894433975, 0.058146849274635315, 0.024550260975956917, 0.07269521802663803, -0.05298478901386261, 0.07404758781194687, -0.0718013271689415, -0.0342666395008564, 0.01621464639902115, -0.03490302339196205, -0.010239542461931705, -0.0025895123835653067, 0.04115841165184975, -0.01612205058336258, 0.08817151933908463, -0.024092430248856544, -0.01062503457069397, -0.07291816920042038, 0.02943248301744461, -0.05834254249930382, 0.009709828533232212, 0.011547911912202835, 0.04327936843037605, -0.012814350426197052, 0.03802916780114174, -0.07422611862421036, 0.07264085859060287, 0.04591652750968933, -0.02002032846212387, -0.054039329290390015, 0.05927721783518791, -0.02956436388194561, -0.10009393841028214, 0.035021472722291946, 0.04577616974711418, -0.001037950860336423, -0.0790439322590828, 0.00044394744327291846, 0.03626367822289467, -0.03441391512751579,